               <note>
                  <date type="foundation" cert="low">17th century</date>
                  <desc type="foundation">Although the name "Gondar" is first mentioned in the
                        <date>14th century</date> to designate a regiment of soldiers and
                     subsequently was used to designate a small market town inhabited by Muslim
                     traders and <persName ref="ETH1274Betaes">Beta ʾƎsrāʾel</persName> craftsme,
                     it developed as a major centre only after <roleName type="title"
                        >ʾaṣe</roleName>
                     <persName ref="PRS4015Fasilada">Fāsiladas</persName> chose it as his camp in
                        <date>1636-1637</date>.</desc>
                  <ab type="history">The town of Gondar is located in today's <placeName ref="LOC6544NorthGondar">North Gondar</placeName> Zone (historically
                        <placeName ref="LOC1713Bagemd">Bagemdǝr</placeName> province) in the
                        <placeName ref="LOC1426Amhara">ʾAmhārā</placeName> Regional State. It
                     evolved from an obscure <date>17th century</date> market town into the
                     flourishing capital of the Ethiopian monarchy, passed through an era of decline
                     and destruction and underwent a slow renaissance in the mid-<date>20th
                        century</date>. Gondar started to flourish after <roleName type="title"
                        >ʾaṣe</roleName>
                     <persName ref="PRS4015Fasilada">Fāsiladas</persName> chose Gondar as his camp
                     in <date>1636/'37</date> to control the collection of customs on the <placeName ref="LOC5339RedSea">Red Sea</placeName> - <placeName ref="LOC5888Tana">
                        Ṭānā</placeName> - <placeName ref="LOC2966Ennary">ʾƎnnāryā</placeName> trade
                     routes. <persName ref="PRS4015Fasilada">Fāsiladas</persName> built the first
                     nucleus including his castle, some churches and his pleasure pool. After him,
                     his son <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName>
                     <persName ref="PRS10375Yohanne">Yoḥānnǝs I</persName> and grandson <roleName
                        type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName>
                     <persName ref="PRS5616IyasuI">Iyāsu I</persName> chose to remain in Gondar and
                     built their own castles and churches. So by the late <date>17th century</date>,
                     Gondar had become a permanent and sizeable settlement where Ethiopian rulers
                     resided when not campaigning and where the highest commerical, political and
                     religious classes gathered around the throne. In the <date>17th century</date>
                     Gondar also became the major commercial centre of northern <placeName
                        ref="LOC3010Ethiop">Ethiopia</placeName>. During the <date>18th
                        century</date>, the royal compound was completed with the construction of
                     castles by <persName ref="PRS3430DawitII">Dāwit III</persName>, <persName
                        ref="PRS2377Bakaffa">Bakāffā</persName> and <persName ref="PRS5617IyasuII"
                        >Iyāsu II</persName>, the church of <placeName ref="LOC1582ASSaSa">ʾAṭṭāṭāmi
                        Mikāʾel</placeName> by <persName ref="PRS3430DawitII">Dāwit III</persName>
                     and various subsidiary building the whole surrounded by a double wall with
                     twelve gates and reinforcing towers. </ab>
                  <ab type="description">Gondar has enjoyed a strategic positio: it is 35 km north
                     of the lake <placeName ref="LOC5888Tana"> Ṭānā</placeName> close to the point
                     where two strategic caravan routes joined. It also benefitted from being
                     surrounded by a semi-cyrcle of mountains and close to fertile lands and water
                     supply. Historically, Gondar population was divided into two main groups that
                     lived in clearly separated quarters and neighbourhoods: the royal court and
                     nobility on the one hand; the merchants, craftsmen and commoners on the other.
                     Muslims and <persName ref="ETH1274Betaes">Beta ʾƎsrāʾel</persName> had to live
                     separated from the Christians and were assigned precise quarters. Gondar is
                     today one of the largest cities in <placeName ref="LOC3010Ethiop"
                        >Ethiopia</placeName>.</ab>
               </note>
